      {"id": "ef_inv_1", "question": "Parlez-_____ français ?", "translation": "(Do you speak French?)", "options": ["vous", "tu", "ils", "nous"], "correct": "vous", "explanation": "Subject-verb inversion is the formal way to ask questions in French. The subject pronoun moves after the verb, connected by a hyphen: 'Parlez-vous.' This is the formal equivalent of 'Est-ce que vous parlez français ?' or the informal 'Vous parlez français ?' (rising intonation). Inversion with 'vous' is the most common in professional and formal contexts. Mastering all three question levels is essential for appropriate register."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_2", "question": "Aime-t-_____ le chocolat ?", "translation": "(Does he/she like chocolate?)", "options": ["il", "elle", "on", "tu"], "correct": "il", "explanation": "When inversion creates a vowel-vowel clash (aime + il), a euphonic 't' is inserted between hyphens: 'aime-t-il.' This only happens with third-person singular (il/elle/on) when the verb ends in a vowel. It doesn't happen with 'tu' (consonant) or plural forms. 'Aime-t-il' / 'aime-t-elle' / 'aime-t-on' all follow this pattern. This euphonic 't' has no meaning — it exists purely for smooth pronunciation. All options could be correct contextually, but the canonical form uses 'il.'"},
      {"id": "ef_inv_3", "question": "Les enfants, sont-_____ prêts ?", "translation": "(Are the children ready?)", "options": ["ils", "elles", "on", "nous"], "correct": "ils", "explanation": "When the subject is a noun (les enfants), French uses 'complex inversion': the noun stays before the verb and a pronoun is added after it: 'Les enfants, sont-ils prêts ?' The comma after 'les enfants' is important. You cannot simply say 'Sont les enfants prêts ?' — that's ungrammatical in French. This double-subject structure is unique to French and essential for formal written and spoken discourse. 'Prêts' agrees with the masculine plural subject."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_4", "question": "Comment a-t-_____ fait cela ?", "translation": "(How did he/she do that?)", "options": ["il", "vous", "tu", "nous"], "correct": "il", "explanation": "Interrogative word + inversion: 'Comment a-t-il fait cela ?' Again, the euphonic 't' appears because 'a' (avoir) ends in a vowel before 'il.' With compound tenses (passé composé here), the subject pronoun goes after the auxiliary: 'a-t-il fait,' not after the past participle. 'Cela' (that) is more formal than 'ça.' This question structure — interrogative + auxiliary-pronoun + participle — is the formal standard for past-tense questions."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_5", "question": "N'avez-_____ pas compris la question ?", "translation": "(Didn't you understand the question?)", "options": ["vous", "tu", "ils", "nous"], "correct": "vous", "explanation": "Negative inversion wraps 'ne...pas' around the inverted verb-pronoun: 'N'avez-vous pas.' The word order is: ne + verb + hyphen + pronoun + pas. This is very formal and common in writing, exams, and professional speech. The informal equivalent would be 'Vous n'avez pas compris ?' (rising intonation). Mastering negative inversion is crucial for formal French — it appears frequently in literature, journalism, and academic texts."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_6", "question": "Pourrait-_____ me passer le sel ?", "translation": "(Could you pass me the salt?)", "options": ["on", "tu", "il", "nous"], "correct": "on", "explanation": "'Pourrait-on' is an extremely useful polite inversion structure. Using 'on' (one/we/someone) with the conditionnel creates an impersonal, very courteous request. 'Pourrait-on' is softer than 'pourriez-vous' because 'on' depersonalizes the request. 'Me passer le sel' — 'passer' means to pass, and the indirect object 'me' (to me) precedes the infinitive. This type of polite request with inversion is quintessentially French formal dining etiquette."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_7", "question": "Quand reviendras-_____ de vacances ?", "translation": "(When will you come back from vacation?)", "options": ["tu", "vous", "il", "nous"], "correct": "tu", "explanation": "'Revenir' in the futur simple: 'reviendras' (tu form, irregular stem 'reviendr-'). Inversion with 'tu' uses a hyphen: 'reviendras-tu.' Note that 'tu' inversion is less common than 'vous' in everyday speech — it appears mainly in literature or between close acquaintances being deliberately formal or playful. 'De vacances' — French says 'revenir de vacances' (plural, no article), while 'être en vacances' means 'to be on vacation.'"},
      {"id": "ef_inv_8", "question": "Votre fils, a-t-_____ réussi ses examens ?", "translation": "(Did your son pass his exams?)", "options": ["il", "elle", "on", "tu"], "correct": "il", "explanation": "Complex inversion with a noun subject: 'Votre fils' (your son) stays in place, and the pronoun 'il' is added after the verb. Euphonic 't' between 'a' and 'il': 'a-t-il.' 'Réussir ses examens' (to pass one's exams) — 'réussir' takes a direct object in French (no preposition), unlike 'réussir à + infinitif.' The possessive 'ses' (his) agrees with 'examens' (plural). This is a typical concerned-parent question structure."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_9", "question": "Où irons-_____ en vacances cette année ?", "translation": "(Where will we go on vacation this year?)", "options": ["nous", "vous", "ils", "on"], "correct": "nous", "explanation": "'Aller' in the futur simple: 'irons' (nous, irregular stem 'ir-'). The inversion 'irons-nous' is a natural way to plan activities together. 'En vacances' (on vacation) — remember the preposition 'en' for 'vacances' in this expression. 'Cette année' (this year) uses the demonstrative adjective 'cette' (feminine, agreeing with 'année'). This planning question demonstrates how inversion works smoothly with 'nous' in future-tense questions."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_10", "question": "Peut-_____ entrer ?", "translation": "(May I come in?)", "options": ["on", "il", "elle", "tu"], "correct": "on", "explanation": "'Peut-on entrer ?' is a supremely polite way to ask permission to enter. Using 'on' (impersonal) instead of 'je peux entrer ?' adds formal distance. No euphonic 't' is needed because 'peut' ends in a consonant. This short question is used when knocking on a door or requesting access. Compare: 'Puis-je entrer ?' (very formal, using the archaic first-person inversion form 'puis-je' instead of 'peux-je,' which is considered incorrect)."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_11", "question": "Combien coûte-t-_____ ce manteau ?", "translation": "(How much does this coat cost?)", "options": ["il", "elle", "on", "tu"], "correct": "il", "explanation": "When asking about price with inversion: 'Combien coûte-t-il ?' The euphonic 't' appears between 'coûte' (ends in vowel sound -e) and 'il.' 'Ce manteau' (this coat) is the real subject, so complex inversion applies: noun before, pronoun after. In casual speech, 'Combien ça coûte ?' or 'C'est combien ?' is far more common. Note: recent French spelling reform makes 'couter' acceptable without the circumflex, but 'coûter' remains standard."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_12", "question": "Savez-_____ où se trouve la gare ?", "translation": "(Do you know where the station is?)", "options": ["vous", "tu", "ils", "on"], "correct": "vous", "explanation": "'Savez-vous' is a formal inversion frequently used to begin polite questions to strangers. 'Où se trouve la gare' is an indirect question (no inversion inside it — the word order is normal after 'où'). 'Se trouver' (to be located) is more formal than 'être': 'Où est la gare ?' is simpler but less elegant. Asking for directions is one of the most practical applications of inversion, making 'savez-vous où...' an essential travel phrase."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_13", "question": "Marie, est-_____ arrivée ?", "translation": "(Has Marie arrived?)", "options": ["elle", "il", "on", "tu"], "correct": "elle", "explanation": "Complex inversion with a feminine noun subject: 'Marie, est-elle arrivée ?' The pronoun 'elle' mirrors the feminine subject. Past participle 'arrivée' agrees in gender with the subject (feminine singular: -ée). 'Arriver' uses 'être' in compound tenses (DR MRS VANDERTRAMP verb). This sentence tests three things simultaneously: complex inversion, auxiliary choice (être), and past participle agreement — a challenging but common combination in formal French."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_14", "question": "Puis-_____ vous poser une question ?", "translation": "(May I ask you a question?)", "options": ["je", "nous", "on", "tu"], "correct": "je", "explanation": "'Puis-je' is the ONLY correct first-person inversion form of 'pouvoir.' You cannot say 'peux-je' — it's considered ungrammatical despite seeming logical. 'Puis' is an archaic form of 'peux' preserved solely for inversion. 'Poser une question à quelqu'un' (to ask someone a question) — note French uses 'poser' (to place/put), not 'demander' for questions. 'Demander' means to ask for/request something. This distinction is a frequent error for English speakers."},
      {"id": "ef_inv_15", "question": "Ne serait-_____ pas mieux de partir maintenant ?", "translation": "(Wouldn't it be better to leave now?)", "options": ["il", "elle", "on", "tu"], "correct": "il", "explanation": "'Ne serait-il pas mieux de...' is an impersonal construction using 'il' (impersonal it) — like 'il faut,' 'il est possible.' The negative inversion 'Ne serait-il pas' wraps ne...pas around the inverted verb-pronoun. The conditionnel 'serait' makes this a tentative suggestion rather than a direct statement. 'Partir maintenant' (to leave now) is the proposed action. This structure is quintessentially French for making subtle, diplomatic suggestions in formal discourse."}
